Research Informed Consent
 
 

  

 Purpose:

 We are conducting a research study to examine people’s ordinary intuitions about how they use words in their everyday life.

  

 Procedures:

 Participation in this study will involve filling out a brief questionnaire.  We anticipate that your involvement will require around 3 to 5 minutes.  You must be at least 18 years old to participate. 

  

 Risks and Benefits:
This research will not benefit you directly, but we
 hope that our results will add to scientific knowledge about people’s 
ordinary intuitions about morality. 

  

 Confidentiality:

 All of your responses will be anonymous.  

  

 Voluntary Participation:

 Participation in this study is completely voluntary.  You
 are free to decline to participate, to end participation at any time 
for any reason.

  

 Questions:

 If you have any questions about this study, you may contact the 
investigator, Pascale Willemsen, by sending an email to pascale.willemsen@philos.uzh.ch

I guess they could have said that he's very generous, but still meant it as a criticism potentially in the sense that they think he is too generous, such as not being careful who he lends things to (and thus doesn't get them back).  However, by definition being "very generous" would be a positive thing, so I still would argue that there is a contradiction because even if they mean to be critical and imply that he's being too generous, they are still saying he's generous (shares with other people), so by definition there is still something positive within that descriptor even if they then went on to criticize him for being *too* generous, so I don't agree that there isn't a contradiction in the original statement (I there is still a contradiction there, because simply saying someone is generous is a positive thing, even if they then went on to criticize them for being overly generous, they've still said something positive just by using the word generous.).
